				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">What Are Your Favorite Restaurants?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Shannon Doyne			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-03-09T09:02:42+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 9, 2015 5:02 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 9, 2015 5:02 am</span>		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/09/what-are-your-favorite-restaurants/" data-title="What Are Your Favorite Restaurants?" data-description="What constitutes a good restaurant?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/08/business/8-MCDONALDS-LN/8-MCDONALDS-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/08/business/8-MCDONALDS-LN/8-MCDONALDS-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/08/business/8-MCDONALDS-LN/8-MCDONALDS-blog480.jpg" id="100000003559762" width="480" height="702" alt="McDonald&#039;s new chief executive has a new vision for the fast-food chain. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/08/business/mcdonalds-seeks-its-fast-food-soul.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="702"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">McDonald's new chief executive has a new vision for the fast-food chain. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/08/business/mcdonalds-seeks-its-fast-food-soul.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Illustration by Jeremy Enecio</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry"><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion151.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion35.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<p class="summary">Questions about issues in the news for students 13 and older.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/">See all Student Opinion Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What are the most important aspects in choosing a restaurant for breakfast, lunch or dinner: cost, speed, taste, heathful menu options, location or something else?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you ever think about a restaurant&#8217;s image &#8212; or your own &#8212; in making your decision? Is it cool to eat at certain places and not others?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-155845"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/08/business/mcdonalds-seeks-its-fast-food-soul.html">&#8220;McDonaldâs Seeks Its Fast-Food Soul,&#8221;</a> Stephanie Strom writes:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">McDonaldâs is having an identity crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For years, it has lurched from showcasing new items â salads! Egg White Delight McMuffins! sliced apples! â to mining nostalgia for its basic Big Macs and fries. Its core customers still line up at the drive-through window for cheap, quick cups of coffee and hash browns. But the company is also trying to appeal to more finicky eaters who have moved onto upstart competitors like Smashburger and Chipotle, which market their quality ingredients and food customization.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Can McDonaldâs be both fast and bespoke? Cheap and high-quality?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Steve Easterbrook seems to think so. Mr. Easterbrook took over as the chief executive of McDonaldâs on March 1, and last week he was in Las Vegas, where the company presented franchisees and suppliers with a new vision of McDonaldâs. That âdestination,â as it was called, was McDonaldâs as âa modern, progressive burger and breakfast restaurantâ where âcustomization and made to orderâ are essential and where executives âalign our food story around the consumerâs definition of quality and value.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8230; Once, McDonaldâs was a place where every American ate now and then. But the fast-food market has splintered, like many other parts of the economy, into the haves and the have-nots. Upscale fast-casual restaurants like Smashburger and Chipotle attract customers who will pay $5.99 for the Classic Smash burger (âhandcraftedâ and âseared and seasoned to orderâ) or $6.65 for a steak burrito (âorganic and local produce where practicalâ). The menu might be full of calories, but it comes with a halo of quality. The McDonaldâs core customer, on the other hand, is still looking for a break: A $3.99 Big Mac, served fast. In fact, roughly two-thirds of its customers order at a drive-through counter.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8230; Mr. Klein is among the few consumers whoâve had a chance to try McDonaldâs latest turnaround effort â a Create Your Own tablet that allows people to custom-build their sandwiches from a menu of meats, toppings and buns. The burger he got, he said, could compete with the more succulent ones at, say, Elevation Burger.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But it also was about $1.50 more than a Big Mac and required him to wait at a table to be served. The new burgers can be ordered only inside restaurants, and because theyâre made from raw patties, not the precooked ones used in the standard burger, they take seven or eight minutes to prepare, an eternity for the typical McDonaldâs customer. âWhen something like two-thirds of the business is drive-through,â Mr. Klein said, âthis is not the solution.â</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students:</strong> Read the entire article, then tell us &#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; How often do you eat at McDonald&#8217;s or other fast-food restaurants?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; The article states that McDonald&#8217;s is having an &#8220;identify crisis.&#8221; Do you agree or disagree? Why? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; What do you think about the Create Your Own tablet concept? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; What are its advantages and disadvantages?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; If you could create a new restaurant chain, what would be its concept? Describe its menu, prices and how the locations would be decorated. </p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students 13 and older</strong> are invited to comment below. Please use only your <strong>first name.</strong> For <a href="//www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/privacysummary.html">privacy policy</a> reasons, we will not publish student comments that include a last name.</p>
